:::summary
Ancient Hebrew is the Semitic language of the Hebrew Bible (Old Testament) and one of the oldest continuously attested literary languages in the world. It was the primary language of ancient Israel and Judah from roughly the twelfth century BC through the second century AD, and it has been preserved as a sacred language of Jewish worship ever since. Modern Hebrew, revived as a spoken language in the nineteenth and twentieth centuries, descends directly from Biblical Hebrew.
:::

