## Origins and Family

Hebrew belongs to the **Semitic** branch of the **Afroasiatic** language family, which also includes Arabic, Aramaic, Akkadian, Ethiopic (Ge'ez), and Maltese. The Semitic languages are characterized by a distinctive **root-and-pattern morphology**: most words are built on three-consonant (triliteral) roots, with different vowel patterns and affixes creating related words from the same root.

For example, the root **ק-ד-ש** (*Q-D-Sh*, conveying the idea of holiness) generates:
- *qodesh* — holiness, what is set apart
- *qadosh* — holy (adjective)
- *qiddesh* — to sanctify
- *miqdash* — sanctuary, temple
- *Kiddush* — the Friday evening sanctification blessing

This root system gives Hebrew (and Semitic languages generally) a remarkable internal coherence, where etymologically related words share visible consonantal skeletons.

Hebrew is most closely related to **Phoenician** and **Ugaritic** and is related to **Aramaic**, which became the dominant language of the ancient Near East after the Assyrian and Babylonian conquests, eventually displacing Hebrew as the spoken vernacular of Jewish communities.

## The Hebrew Alphabet

Hebrew is written in an **abjad** — an alphabet that represents only consonants. The reader supplies the vowels from context. Modern printed Hebrew adds small marks below and above letters called **niqqud** (vowel points) to aid learners; the biblical text was originally written without them. The Hebrew alphabet has 22 letters, written right to left.

